We note that we can represent the moves at index i as: 
   b_i = k_i * a_i, where k_i is an integer (could be positive, negative, or zero) but note that initially b_i=0, so we are effectively setting b_i to a multiple of a_i. We require: b_0 < b_1 < ... < b_{n-1}

We are to minimize the total number of moves, which is the sum of absolute values of k_i?

And the total moves at index i is |k_i|. So the total moves is sum_i |k_i|. But note: we are allowed to do any number of moves on any index arbitrarily. So we are free to choose any integers k_i. The problem becomes: choose integers k_0, k_1, ..., k_{n-1} such that:
   k_0 * a_0 < k_1 * a_1 < ... < k_{n-1} * a_{n-1}
and minimize T = |k_0| + |k_1| + ... + |k_{n-1}|.

